            <fr:title text="Heine-Cantor theorem">Heine-Cantor theorem</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Gunning's <fr:link href="/gunning-2017-introduction/" title="An Introduction to Analysis" uri="http://localhost:8000/gunning-2017-introduction/" display-uri="gunning-2017-introduction" type="local">An Introduction to Analysis</fr:link> Theorem 3.18</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Royden and Fitzpatrick's <fr:link href="/royden-2010-real/" title="Real Analysis" uri="http://localhost:8000/royden-2010-real/" display-uri="royden-2010-real" type="local">Real Analysis</fr:link>, Ch. 9 Proposition 23</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(Y,\rho )]]></fr:tex> be <fr:link href="/ca-000K/" title="Metric Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000K/" display-uri="ca-000K" type="local">Metric Space</fr:link>s. Assume that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ca-001T/" title="Compact subset of a metric space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001T/" display-uri="ca-001T" type="local">compact</fr:link>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  Y]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ca-001L/" title="Continuous function between metric spaces" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001L/" display-uri="ca-001L" type="local">continuous function</fr:link>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ca-001P/" title="Uniformly Continuous function" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-001P/" display-uri="ca-001P" type="local">uniformly continuous</fr:link>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>12</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p><fr:link href="/nst-002J/" title="Proof by contradiction" uri="http://localhost:8000/nst-002J/" display-uri="nst-002J" type="local">Proof by contradiction</fr:link>. Assume for contradiction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is not uniformly continuous. Then there exists an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon >0]]></fr:tex> such that for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\delta >0]]></fr:tex> and for every <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b\in  X]]></fr:tex> we have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[d(a,b)<\delta \quad \hbox {and}\quad \rho (f(a),f(b))\geq \varepsilon .]]></fr:tex>
Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(X,d)]]></fr:tex> is compact, it is <fr:link href="/ca-0022/" title="Sequentially compact subset" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0022/" display-uri="ca-0022" type="local">sequentially compact</fr:link> by <fr:link href="/ca-0023/" title="Characterization of compactness for metric spaces" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0023/" display-uri="ca-0023" type="local">Characterization of compactness for metric spaces</fr:link>. Then for each <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex>, there exists <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n}\in  X]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[y_{n}\in  X]]></fr:tex> such that
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[d(x_{n},y_{n})<\frac {1}{n}\quad \hbox {and}\quad \rho (f(x_{n}),f(y_{n}))\geq \varepsilon .]]></fr:tex>
But by <fr:link href="/ca-0022/" title="Sequentially compact subset" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-0022/" display-uri="ca-0022" type="local">sequential compactness</fr:link> there exists an <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> and a subsequence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x_{n_{k}})]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x_{n_{k}}\to  x]]></fr:tex> converges. Then using the triangle inequality, we have
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align}
d(y_{n_{k}},x) & \leq  d(y_{n_{k}},x_{n_{k}}) + d(x_{n_{k}},x)\\
&\leq \frac {1}{n_{k}}  + d(x_{n_{k}},x),
\end {align}]]></fr:tex>
which goes to zero for sufficiently large <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[n_{k}]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(y_{n_{k}})\to  x]]></fr:tex>. Then by continuity of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex>, their images (using the triangle inequality):
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x_{n_{k}}), f(y_{n_{k}}))\leq \rho (f(x_{n_{k}}), f(x)) + \rho (f(x), f(y_{n_{k}})),]]></fr:tex>
which goes to zero by continuity. But this contradicts <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rho (f(x_{n_{k}}),f(x))\geq \varepsilon ]]></fr:tex>, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> must be uniformly continuous.</html:p><html:span class="qed">âˆŽ</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
